WEBVTT

00:00:29.827 --> 00:00:31.949
Welcome to this evening edition of the

00:00:32.029 --> 00:00:34.691
Ocean Studio here as part of the Yahowah

00:00:34.710 --> 00:00:35.192
blog.

00:00:35.731 --> 00:00:37.213
I'm here with Wookie.

00:00:37.232 --> 00:00:39.295
We'll see how long he wants to participate

00:00:39.414 --> 00:00:40.695
in this program.

00:00:41.457 --> 00:00:43.317
I wanted to begin by just having an

00:00:44.018 --> 00:00:45.079
interesting chat.

00:00:45.179 --> 00:00:48.963
I finished a phone call with one of

00:00:49.003 --> 00:00:51.746
my dearest and longest term friends.

00:00:51.886 --> 00:00:52.886
His name is Joe.

00:00:52.947 --> 00:00:53.406
He was the

00:00:54.061 --> 00:00:56.444
man who wrote the original code for a

00:00:56.645 --> 00:00:59.146
company that we took public many years

00:00:59.207 --> 00:00:59.546
ago.

00:00:59.606 --> 00:01:02.630
He actually wrote far more sophisticated

00:01:02.970 --> 00:01:07.915
code than currently runs Amazon for our

00:01:08.763 --> 00:01:11.944
our online.com retail operation,

00:01:12.805 --> 00:01:15.606
really genius work that he was able to

00:01:15.647 --> 00:01:16.326
do for us.

00:01:16.968 --> 00:01:19.168
And now we're working on things like

00:01:19.868 --> 00:01:22.370
presenting all of my translations on the

00:01:22.391 --> 00:01:24.231
YadaYah website,

00:01:24.591 --> 00:01:26.612
but doing so so that you can see

00:01:27.894 --> 00:01:30.176
every verse of, say,

00:01:30.516 --> 00:01:32.697
Bare'syth Genesis that I have translated,

00:01:32.837 --> 00:01:33.638
one after the other,

00:01:34.058 --> 00:01:35.879
and every time that I've translated them,

00:01:35.959 --> 00:01:38.400
how in a different context and different

00:01:38.441 --> 00:01:41.141
time I may have rendered them.

00:01:41.522 --> 00:01:42.483
In fact, I would not may,

00:01:42.582 --> 00:01:44.004
I would have rendered them differently,

00:01:44.024 --> 00:01:45.105
because each time you go through,

00:01:45.125 --> 00:01:46.344
you're looking at the words and all of

00:01:46.364 --> 00:01:49.546
the conjugations and the stems and the

00:01:49.606 --> 00:01:51.828
pronouns and the like.

00:01:53.188 --> 00:01:54.810
It's an art form as you're trying to

00:01:54.930 --> 00:01:55.189
render it.

00:01:55.209 --> 00:01:56.051
And the more you learn,

00:01:56.150 --> 00:01:58.912
the more you recognize patterns in God's

00:01:58.971 --> 00:02:02.453
testimony and can convey his intended

00:02:02.513 --> 00:02:04.093
meaning more accurately.

00:02:04.114 --> 00:02:05.894
And they're always amplified translations.

00:02:06.534 --> 00:02:08.235
And so we were having a conversation about

00:02:08.276 --> 00:02:08.496
this.

00:02:08.575 --> 00:02:11.097
And for those who may not know,

00:02:11.137 --> 00:02:13.758
who have not been to YadaYah.com,

00:02:13.818 --> 00:02:15.438
where all of these books that I have

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:16.599
written are presented free,

00:02:17.180 --> 00:02:19.260
is that twenty five years ago,

00:02:19.941 --> 00:02:23.331
I invented an entirely new way of

00:02:23.372 --> 00:02:24.054
translating.

00:02:25.194 --> 00:02:25.995
Prior to this time,

00:02:26.034 --> 00:02:28.697
no one had done anything anywhere close to

00:02:28.717 --> 00:02:28.977
this,

00:02:29.056 --> 00:02:31.337
which is it's not only an Amplified

00:02:31.377 --> 00:02:32.018
translation.

00:02:32.057 --> 00:02:35.699
And I realize there's one publication of a

00:02:35.758 --> 00:02:38.060
Bible that calls itself an Amplified

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:39.580
version, but it's not.

00:02:40.241 --> 00:02:41.942
It's just like every other version.

00:02:42.481 --> 00:02:44.802
The first ever Amplified translation where

00:02:44.923 --> 00:02:47.683
if there were twenty words that would

00:02:47.843 --> 00:02:50.224
properly render a single Hebrew word,

00:02:50.906 --> 00:02:51.186
I would...

00:02:51.985 --> 00:02:54.727
present all twenty of them that made sense

00:02:54.766 --> 00:02:55.987
within that context,

00:02:56.087 --> 00:02:57.769
not overwhelming the reader by putting

00:02:58.209 --> 00:03:02.110
maybe the three or four most important of

00:03:02.151 --> 00:03:04.231
them in a bold font.

00:03:04.752 --> 00:03:07.294
And then within the parenthetical in a

00:03:07.373 --> 00:03:08.294
standard font,

00:03:08.794 --> 00:03:10.936
I would present many of the other

00:03:11.955 --> 00:03:13.497
possibilities so that you are not

00:03:13.557 --> 00:03:14.338
shortchanged,

00:03:14.778 --> 00:03:17.241
recognizing that God may have intended and

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:19.723
probably did all of these things for us

00:03:19.764 --> 00:03:20.163
to know.

00:03:20.724 --> 00:03:22.806
So it's the first real amplified

00:03:22.847 --> 00:03:25.068
translation where the full meaning of

00:03:25.128 --> 00:03:26.911
every word is presented,

00:03:26.991 --> 00:03:31.895
not just the translator's decision as to

00:03:32.355 --> 00:03:34.777
what they think was the only word being

00:03:34.837 --> 00:03:35.258
conveyed.

00:03:36.896 --> 00:03:38.497
And I think that short changes you,

00:03:38.538 --> 00:03:39.959
and I think it's a terrible way to

00:03:40.038 --> 00:03:40.459
go about.

00:03:40.538 --> 00:03:44.501
I'm not here to presume that if God

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:48.462
used a word that can have ten definitions

00:03:48.483 --> 00:03:50.183
that are all pertinent in that context,

00:03:50.503 --> 00:03:52.625
that we should shortchange anybody,

00:03:52.664 --> 00:03:53.425
including God,

00:03:53.705 --> 00:03:54.966
to only representing one of them.

00:03:55.026 --> 00:03:56.986
So it was the first ever genuine,

00:03:57.606 --> 00:03:58.608
amplified translation.

00:03:59.087 --> 00:04:01.629
It was also the first where the generic

00:04:01.689 --> 00:04:05.012
form of the Hebrew word being translated

00:04:05.352 --> 00:04:06.393
was actually print,

00:04:06.592 --> 00:04:09.534
put right inside of the translation

00:04:09.594 --> 00:04:10.014
itself.

00:04:10.496 --> 00:04:12.257
So that after the bold copy,

00:04:12.276 --> 00:04:14.618
which is the amplified translation itself,

00:04:15.459 --> 00:04:16.759
Inside of a parenthetical,

00:04:16.778 --> 00:04:18.980
the first word written in italics would be

00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:23.762
the most genitive form of the Hebrew word.

00:04:24.081 --> 00:04:25.302
And I'd write it, you know,

00:04:25.341 --> 00:04:27.182
let's say that it was a Hebrew word

00:04:27.223 --> 00:04:28.002
that was a verb,

00:04:28.423 --> 00:04:33.225
and it had a prefix of a pronoun

00:04:33.285 --> 00:04:37.105
like he or she or, you know, I.

00:04:38.526 --> 00:04:43.790
Or it had a suffix of a pronoun

00:04:43.829 --> 00:04:47.612
like me or your.

00:04:48.252 --> 00:04:52.394
And then it perhaps had a stem that

00:04:52.694 --> 00:04:55.636
gave it additional meaning,

00:04:56.197 --> 00:05:02.259
like the Hiphil or one of the seven

00:05:02.319 --> 00:05:03.880
stems in Hebrew.

00:05:04.949 --> 00:05:07.350
that convey meanings, like the qal,

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:11.132
which would be considered a literal

00:05:11.192 --> 00:05:15.014
interpretation of those words, the Piel,

00:05:15.555 --> 00:05:17.576
the Nifal, or other examples.

00:05:17.776 --> 00:05:18.718
And then there's moods,

00:05:19.358 --> 00:05:20.158
also in the Hebrew,

00:05:20.178 --> 00:05:22.019
that convey volition in first, second,

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:23.201
and third person.

00:05:24.021 --> 00:05:25.961
The cohortative, for example,

00:05:25.982 --> 00:05:27.822
is first person expression of volition.

00:05:28.303 --> 00:05:31.685
And then there are four conjunctions

00:05:31.745 --> 00:05:31.925
that...

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:40.553
that convey time relative to the verb,

00:05:40.593 --> 00:05:43.675
whether it's ongoing or completed

00:05:44.055 --> 00:05:45.355
conjugation, I should say.

00:05:45.795 --> 00:05:50.677
And these are the four ways of conveying

00:05:50.737 --> 00:05:51.317
whether the...

00:05:52.437 --> 00:05:54.939
Action of the verb is taking place over

00:05:54.999 --> 00:05:58.319
a prolonged period or is for a finite

00:05:58.358 --> 00:05:58.720
period,

00:05:59.339 --> 00:06:02.461
and time can be expressed relative to the

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:05.821
verb in four different conjugations.

00:06:06.261 --> 00:06:08.762
The most common are the perfect and

00:06:08.822 --> 00:06:09.242
imperfect,

00:06:09.281 --> 00:06:10.723
with the perfect being constrained in

00:06:10.783 --> 00:06:12.202
time, either in the past, present,

00:06:12.223 --> 00:06:12.702
or future,

00:06:13.202 --> 00:06:15.704
and the imperfect being unrestrained in

00:06:15.783 --> 00:06:16.103
time.

00:06:17.163 --> 00:06:20.206
recognizing that no verb is stuck in time.

00:06:20.247 --> 00:06:20.786
In Hebrew,

00:06:22.108 --> 00:06:24.209
all verbs are true throughout time.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:28.432
So if I were to use the verb

00:06:28.853 --> 00:06:33.115
Hayah, meaning is, was, or will be,

00:06:33.815 --> 00:06:34.357
all of those

00:06:35.057 --> 00:06:38.819
are true unless the very context tells us

00:06:39.259 --> 00:06:41.420
that this is something that has not taken

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:42.961
place where I can then render it as

00:06:43.021 --> 00:06:45.423
will or this is something we know has

00:06:45.463 --> 00:06:47.125
taken place in the past where I can

00:06:47.185 --> 00:06:51.827
say was or so will be or was

00:06:51.927 --> 00:06:54.110
and if it is something that is concurrent

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:56.692
with the discussion you can say is but

00:06:58.132 --> 00:07:00.334
all from Hayah and every verb is

00:07:00.593 --> 00:07:02.435
unconstrained in time it's kind of like

00:07:02.495 --> 00:07:04.336
light on a photon of light all time

00:07:04.396 --> 00:07:08.500
exists simultaneously. And so I'm the first

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:13.083
to consider every one of these uh factors

00:07:13.142 --> 00:07:16.105
but then render the actual verb and its

00:07:16.185 --> 00:07:19.827
most uh genitive form because that's the

00:07:19.867 --> 00:07:21.009
only way you can look it up if

00:07:21.048 --> 00:07:22.870
it's all loaded with the stems and the

00:07:22.911 --> 00:07:26.132
conjugations and the pronouns and also

00:07:26.153 --> 00:07:26.913
with uh

00:07:28.194 --> 00:07:28.913
conjecture,

00:07:29.475 --> 00:07:32.235
so it's got prepositions which are all

00:07:32.295 --> 00:07:35.836
attached to the verb, conjugations,

00:07:36.857 --> 00:07:38.517
then you'll never be able to look it

00:07:38.577 --> 00:07:38.718
up.

00:07:39.557 --> 00:07:42.718
So I presented the Hebrew term in the

00:07:42.759 --> 00:07:44.779
most generic form that you can copy and

00:07:44.819 --> 00:07:45.139
paste

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:47.980
and any search engine and it will verify

00:07:48.281 --> 00:07:49.982
the meanings that I have chosen so you're

00:07:50.002 --> 00:07:52.103
in a position to prove that my

00:07:52.142 --> 00:07:54.024
translations are accurate no one else has

00:07:54.064 --> 00:07:56.505
ever had the audacity to give you the

00:07:56.526 --> 00:07:58.786
tools to actually verify their

00:07:58.826 --> 00:08:02.468
translations but I did and it's a huge

00:08:02.509 --> 00:08:05.591
tool to build confidence uh between you

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:09.012
and I um and so there's just nothing

00:08:09.151 --> 00:08:11.052
like these translations that have ever

00:08:11.192 --> 00:08:13.134
existed and if a uh

00:08:14.415 --> 00:08:17.076
passage was included in the Dead Sea

00:08:17.115 --> 00:08:17.656
Scrolls,

00:08:18.175 --> 00:08:20.057
I looked up every single one of them

00:08:20.096 --> 00:08:21.976
to see if there was a variance between

00:08:22.016 --> 00:08:23.757
the Dead Sea Scrolls and the Masoretic

00:08:23.798 --> 00:08:24.137
text.

00:08:24.658 --> 00:08:26.098
And if there was,

00:08:26.257 --> 00:08:30.178
I made my translation based upon the Dead

00:08:30.199 --> 00:08:30.819
Sea Scrolls.

00:08:30.858 --> 00:08:32.460
So you would have the oldest

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:36.581
extant version of the truth as it came

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:39.822
from God and in the Hebrew for example

00:08:39.861 --> 00:08:42.143
there's about a fourteen percent

00:08:42.202 --> 00:08:44.224
difference between the Masoretic text and

00:08:44.244 --> 00:08:47.144
the Dead Sea Scrolls so by doing that

00:08:47.225 --> 00:08:47.725
we we

00:08:48.664 --> 00:08:51.467
uh afford you the opportunity to know what

00:08:51.488 --> 00:08:54.389
the oldest witness says and you have that

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.672
correction then I did something no one

00:08:56.711 --> 00:08:59.674
else has ever done before which I scrubbed

00:08:59.835 --> 00:09:03.317
every word of the Masoretic diacritical

00:09:03.437 --> 00:09:05.860
markings where I came to realize that the

00:09:05.921 --> 00:09:09.123
Hebrew alphabet contains uh

00:09:10.051 --> 00:09:12.692
five vowels and seventeen consonants

00:09:12.711 --> 00:09:14.631
amongst the twenty-two letters so the

00:09:14.652 --> 00:09:17.153
diacritical markings were really just a

00:09:17.212 --> 00:09:20.333
means that the master reads created in the

00:09:20.394 --> 00:09:23.595
eleventh uh and twelfth centuries CE uh

00:09:24.855 --> 00:09:27.696
you know we're dealing with now uh twenty

00:09:27.755 --> 00:09:30.317
five hundred years after the Towrah was

00:09:30.356 --> 00:09:33.337
written uh to interpret it religiously the

00:09:33.357 --> 00:09:36.298
way they wanted it interpreted and so they

00:09:36.359 --> 00:09:36.619
made

00:09:37.970 --> 00:09:40.071
different words mean different things

00:09:40.131 --> 00:09:41.371
based on when they mark them.

00:09:41.773 --> 00:09:43.053
And so I scrubbed at all of that

00:09:43.114 --> 00:09:46.875
and I share with you every meaning that

00:09:47.035 --> 00:09:51.820
is based upon the word as it appears

00:09:51.860 --> 00:09:53.860
in the original text without all of those

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:54.400
markings.

00:09:54.461 --> 00:09:58.043
So you're going back to divine writ as

00:09:58.104 --> 00:09:59.024
it was inspired.

00:09:59.644 --> 00:10:00.525
In this case now,

00:10:00.985 --> 00:10:02.967
three thousand five hundred years ago with

00:10:02.988 --> 00:10:03.448
the Towrah,

00:10:04.389 --> 00:10:06.051
twenty five hundred years ago with the

00:10:06.071 --> 00:10:08.052
last of the prophets, with Malachi.

00:10:08.894 --> 00:10:11.355
Again, no one's ever done that with you.

00:10:11.395 --> 00:10:14.438
So it became a very different way of

00:10:14.759 --> 00:10:16.941
us being able to communicate and to reveal

00:10:17.081 --> 00:10:17.741
information.

00:10:19.678 --> 00:10:20.418
In doing that,

00:10:20.958 --> 00:10:23.940
I realized that there are two letters that

00:10:25.301 --> 00:10:29.142
can make very similar vowel sounds.

00:10:29.162 --> 00:10:30.501
You can have the E sound or the

00:10:30.601 --> 00:10:31.702
A sound, the I,

00:10:32.602 --> 00:10:37.365
from the Aleph or the Ayin in Hebrew.

00:10:38.065 --> 00:10:41.446
And the scholastic pedantic way to deal

00:10:41.485 --> 00:10:44.206
with it was a closed or open quote

00:10:44.307 --> 00:10:47.148
representing the Aleph to differentiate it

00:10:47.207 --> 00:10:47.967
from the Ayin.

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:51.493
problem with that is that Word has a

00:10:51.533 --> 00:10:54.254
field day with open and closed quotes,

00:10:54.695 --> 00:10:56.417
single quotes, and we'll decide,

00:10:56.437 --> 00:10:57.778
do you want it as, you know,

00:10:57.798 --> 00:11:00.899
it's a smart quote or just a standard

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:03.361
or, and it will go vertical.

00:11:03.501 --> 00:11:03.961
And in fact,

00:11:04.042 --> 00:11:06.644
almost all computer presentations now just

00:11:06.683 --> 00:11:07.625
show the open and quote,

00:11:07.664 --> 00:11:08.946
quote as a vertical slash.

00:11:08.985 --> 00:11:11.287
They don't make a differentiation between

00:11:11.307 --> 00:11:11.868
the

00:11:12.525 --> 00:11:14.707
the open quote or the close quote.

00:11:15.249 --> 00:11:18.572
And so the old scholastic way of dealing

00:11:18.611 --> 00:11:19.231
with this,

00:11:19.371 --> 00:11:21.693
which very few people followed anyway,

00:11:22.554 --> 00:11:24.797
is rendered moot because of the nature of

00:11:25.158 --> 00:11:29.942
both the way word processes these quotes

00:11:30.062 --> 00:11:32.443
and also because all

00:11:33.485 --> 00:11:38.469
Modern online presentations default to the

00:11:39.168 --> 00:11:39.549
strict,

00:11:40.149 --> 00:11:43.451
a quote is a vertical line and it

00:11:43.471 --> 00:11:45.693
does not differentiate between open quotes

00:11:45.734 --> 00:11:46.475
and close quotes.

00:11:46.715 --> 00:11:48.895
So we came up just two days ago

00:11:49.397 --> 00:11:50.778
with our own superscript.

00:11:51.357 --> 00:11:52.839
So that if it's an Ayin,

00:11:52.918 --> 00:11:55.240
I have a superscript version of the little

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:57.681
eyeball that was the original letter for

00:11:57.721 --> 00:11:58.181
the Ayin.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:11:59.902
And a close quote,

00:11:59.981 --> 00:12:03.303
if it was an Aleph, is the...

00:12:06.086 --> 00:12:09.610
So the ram's head or bull's head that

00:12:09.691 --> 00:12:11.453
is used for the Aleph,

00:12:11.474 --> 00:12:12.735
we have a superscript of it.

00:12:12.794 --> 00:12:15.238
So now you're reading a word in the

00:12:15.278 --> 00:12:17.500
text and you're going to know, well,

00:12:17.541 --> 00:12:20.924
does Yada end in an Aleph or an

00:12:21.065 --> 00:12:21.264
Ayin?

00:12:21.345 --> 00:12:22.486
And as it turns out,

00:12:22.966 --> 00:12:24.528
Yada ends in an Ayin.

00:12:25.671 --> 00:12:28.133
Ayin, which is the eyeball, as does Zarowa,

00:12:28.313 --> 00:12:32.278
as does Shabuah and Taruwah.

00:12:32.918 --> 00:12:34.561
They all follow that same pattern.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.222
And so now you can actually see the

00:12:36.263 --> 00:12:38.926
pattern in the text as we're going to

00:12:38.946 --> 00:12:42.168
go back and redo all the books for

00:12:42.229 --> 00:12:42.990
this new pattern.

00:12:43.029 --> 00:12:44.652
And I'm writing the current book,

00:12:44.972 --> 00:12:45.692
Coming Home Four

00:12:46.453 --> 00:12:46.813
using it.

00:12:47.955 --> 00:12:49.416
So it's just a really an interesting

00:12:49.456 --> 00:12:49.875
process.

00:12:49.895 --> 00:12:51.817
And so we're also trying to have an

00:12:51.857 --> 00:12:55.559
interactive glossary with our translation

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:57.601
so that the words are underlined and you

00:12:57.621 --> 00:12:58.282
can click on them.

00:12:58.621 --> 00:13:00.744
But the challenge with that is there

00:13:00.764 --> 00:13:03.105
really is on the transliteration no way to

00:13:03.205 --> 00:13:05.547
differentiate currently between an aleph

00:13:05.647 --> 00:13:06.246
and an Ayin.

00:13:06.807 --> 00:13:09.529
And so you can get the wrong word.

